INFORMATION RETRIEVAL RELEVANCE — HOW TO MEASURE “ABOUTNESS” PRECISELY
025.4 — Information Storage & Retrieval
================================================================================

“Aboutness” is the core of topical relevance: the degree to which a document is
*about* the topic expressed by a query (or information need). It is distinct from
other relevance facets (utility, novelty, authority, recency, user task fit, etc.).

Precise measurement has two layers:
  1. Operational / system-side   (what IR engines actually compute)
  2. Evaluative / gold-standard  (how humans or multi-faceted judgments define
     ground truth)

1. CLASSIC AND STILL-FOUNDATIONAL FORMULATIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Cranfield / TREC paradigm (the empirical gold standard)
  • Binary or graded human judgments: “Is this document relevant to this topic?”
  • Aboutness is treated as a binary or 4–5-level graded relation between a fixed
    topic statement and a document.
  • Metrics: Precision@k, MAP, nDCG, ERR, RBP.
    These measure ranking quality relative to human aboutness labels, not
    aboutness itself.
  • Limitation: aboutness is left as an unanalyzed primitive; judges are
    instructed “if the document is about the topic…”.

Logical / model-theoretic view (early formal IR)
  • A document D is about a query Q if D ⊨ Q under some interpretation
    (Boolean, fuzzy, or probabilistic).
  • Van Rijsbergen’s logical uncertainty principle and the “aboutness” relation
    D ⊨_a Q.
  • Modern descendants: description-logic based IR, ontology-mediated retrieval.

2. VECTOR-SPACE AND PROBABILISTIC MEASURES OF ABOUTNESS (COMPUTABLE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Approach                  | Aboutness signal                  | Precision of “about”     | Key idea / formula
--------------------------+-----------------------------------+--------------------------+-----------------------------------------------
TF-IDF / BM25             | Term overlap weighted by rarity   | Coarse; bag-of-words     | BM25 score sum
Language models           | Query likelihood P(Q|D) or KL     | Better topical focus     | Dirichlet / Jelinek-Mercer smoothed
Dense retrieval           | Cosine / dot product in embedding | Strong semantic          | sim(E_Q, E_D)  (BERT, Contriever, E5, GTE…)
