3. MORE PRECISE, THEORETICALLY GROUNDED NOTIONS OF ABOUTNESS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A. Topical compositionality / aboutness operators
   • A document is about topic T to degree α if its content can be decomposed
     into a core about T plus residual.
   • Formalized via:
       – Lattice theory (aboutness as meet/join in a concept lattice)
       – Rough-set or fuzzy-set approximations of the topic
       – Information-theoretic: I(D; T) / H(T)  (normalized mutual information)

B. Intentional vs. extentional aboutness
   • Extensional : the set of objects/events the document talks about overlaps
                   the set the query is about.
   • Intentional : the document is written with the purpose of conveying
                   information about the topic (harder; needs discourse/intent
                   modeling).

C. Modern neural + symbolic hybrids
   • Query expansion / rewriting with LLMs → better capture of aboutness facets.
   • Chain-of-thought or “reason about the topic first” prompting before retrieval.
   • Atomic fact / claim decomposition: break query into atomic propositions;
     measure coverage + fidelity of document sentences to those atoms.
   • Entailment-based: D is about Q if a strong NLI model judges that D entails
     the core propositions of Q (or vice-versa for specificity).

D. Multi-dimensional / graded aboutness
   Recent TREC and SIGIR work treats aboutness as multi-graded and multi-aspect:
     – Topicality
     – Coverage      (how much of the topic)
     – Specificity / focus  (how little off-topic material)
     – Depth
     – Authority on the topic
   Human assessors or LLM-as-judge score each dimension separately; aggregation
   yields a richer aboutness vector.

4. PRACTICAL RECIPE FOR MEASURING ABOUTNESS PRECISELY TODAY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Define the information need as a structured object, not a string:
     Core topic + facets + must-include / must-exclude + granularity
     (overview vs. deep dive).

2. Obtain high-quality labels
     • Prefer multi-grade + multi-aspect human judgments.
     • Or high-agreement LLM judges with carefully engineered rubrics
       (“Rate topical aboutness 0–3; justify with evidence spans”).

3. System-side scorer (choose by latency/accuracy needs)
     • Fast:     BM25 + dense bi-encoder (hybrid)
     • Accurate: cross-encoder or LLM re-ranker prompted explicitly for aboutness
                 (“How topically about is this document to the query?
                  Score 0–10 and list supporting passages”).

4. Evaluation metrics that respect graded aboutness
     • nDCG, ERR, RBP with graded gains
     • Aspect-aware metrics (e.g. α-nDCG if multiple intents)
     • Coverage + fidelity metrics if using claim decomposition

5. Diagnostic tools
     • Attention / attribution maps showing which parts of the document drive
       the aboutness score
     • Counterfactual: remove sentences and measure score drop → identifies the
       aboutness-bearing content

5. OPEN RESEARCH FRONTIERS (WHERE “PRECISE” IS STILL BEING DEFINED)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  • Causal aboutness (does the document cause the user to learn about the topic?)
  • Dynamic / session aboutness (aboutness relative to evolving knowledge state)
  • Cross-lingual and multimodal aboutness
  • Formal verification of aboutness via theorem provers + LLMs (embryonic)
  • Relational / geometric views of aboutness
      (topic and document as points or trajectories in a latent manifold;
       aboutness as geodesic proximity or flux through a topic region)

BOTTOM LINE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

There is no single scalar that perfectly captures aboutness.

The most precise current practice is:
  • multi-aspect graded human (or carefully validated LLM) labels as ground truth
  • hybrid sparse + dense + cross-encoder scoring for ranking
  • evaluation with graded, intent-aware metrics

